{"_id":"QMG7jnFvUhm05LSR","name":"GM Basic Moves","content":"<h2>After every move: “What do you do?”</h2>\n<ul>\n<li>@Compendium[masks-newgeneration-unofficial.masks-gm-moves.Ayqd4mmwXjR5xEsL]{Inflict a Condition}</li>\n<li>@Compendium[masks-newgeneration-unofficial.masks-gm-moves.RmA3vo8I931ma2BD]{Take Influence Over Someone}</li>\n<li>@Compendium[masks-newgeneration-unofficial.masks-gm-moves.nR1zEyKYqWuzf64r]{Bring Them Together}</li>\n<li>@Compendium[masks-newgeneration-unofficial.masks-gm-moves.75sYF9XK9OJstSde]{Capture Someone}</li>\n<li>@Compendium[masks-newgeneration-unofficial.masks-gm-moves.YkMMTr4W0ibow04I]{Put Innocents in Danger}</li>\n<li>@Compendium[masks-newgeneration-unofficial.masks-gm-moves.3vvole9MCKAsq2wT]{Show the Costs of Collateral Damage}</li>\n<li>@Compendium[masks-newgeneration-unofficial.masks-gm-moves.YiEo7fRSYnd0OVD0]{Reveal the Future, Subtly or Directly}</li>\n<li>@Compendium[masks-newgeneration-unofficial.masks-gm-moves.UGx4gfuXxujL6sqJ]{Announce Between-Panel Threats}</li>\n<li>@Compendium[masks-newgeneration-unofficial.masks-gm-moves.o7t08ghJ0DlhpXq1]{Make Them Pay a Price for Victory}</li>\n<li>@Compendium[masks-newgeneration-unofficial.masks-gm-moves.pmqVxC2g3qJqRB6i]{Turn Their Move Back on Them}</li>\n<li>@Compendium[masks-newgeneration-unofficial.masks-gm-moves.gQE0SHsotSj5vU3z]{Tell them the Possible Consequences and Ask}</li>\n<li>@Compendium[masks-newgeneration-unofficial.masks-gm-moves.DgnBwrRxS6aMCimh]{Tell Them Who They Are or Who They Should Be}</li>\n<li>@Compendium[masks-newgeneration-unofficial.masks-gm-moves.CkFuLcEFEkfK2Xie]{Bring an NPC to Rash Decisions and Hard Conclusions}</li>\n<li>@Compendium[masks-newgeneration-unofficial.masks-gm-moves.kOaL7qLh8vjBfOLX]{Activate the Downsides of their Abilities and Relationships}</li>\n<li>@Compendium[masks-newgeneration-unofficial.masks-gm-moves.uacO1mEypo2ZJG1j]{Make a Playbook Move}</li>\n<li>@Compendium[masks-newgeneration-unofficial.masks-gm-moves.8QOq3yKgpBgOIwZG]{Make a Villain Move}</li>\n</ul>\n<p> </p>\n<p> </p>\n<p> </p>","folder":null,"sort":0,"permission":{"default":0,"RZXbWcV7kggw6gJH":3},"flags":{}}
{"_id":"RmA3vo8I931ma2BD","name":"Take Influence Over Someone","content":"<p>Young heroes often leave themselves vulnerable. They open themselves up and find themselves affected by the words of people they thought they could ignore. That’s you taking Influence over someone. You’re flagging that the PCs don’t have as much control over their own emotions as they might want...that they don’t always get to pick and choose whose words matter to them.</p>","folder":null,"sort":0,"permission":{"default":0,"RZXbWcV7kggw6gJH":3},"flags":{"cf":{"id":"temp_4h5r03e5nxs","color":"#000000"}}}
{"_id":"UGx4gfuXxujL6sqJ","name":"Announce Between-Panel Threats","content":"<p>Halcyon City marches on, even while the heroes deal with other problems and issues. Between scenes, outside of the conversation, villains may take action that threatens the heroes and their interests. When you need to make a move, you can announce those threats. Draw attention to them. Show a villain cackling ominously, or have them make veiled allusions to what they’ve done—or just straight up announce it, publicly. Villains can be a pompous bunch, after all.</p>","folder":null,"sort":0,"permission":{"default":0,"RZXbWcV7kggw6gJH":3},"flags":{"cf":{"id":"temp_4h5r03e5nxs","color":"#000000"}}}
{"_id":"YiEo7fRSYnd0OVD0","name":"Reveal the Future, Subtly or Directly","content":"<p>The characters in MASKS are the future of this city. They’ll determine what Halcyon City becomes. So keep showing them the future and the possible paths they’re on. Sometimes you can do this in a straightforwardly comic book fashion—literally, showing them the future through time portals or future versions of themselves or whatever. But other times, do it indirectly, through current figures that might represent what they’re becoming.</p>","folder":null,"sort":0,"permission":{"default":0,"RZXbWcV7kggw6gJH":3},"flags":{"cf":{"id":"temp_4h5r03e5nxs","color":"#000000"}}}
{"_id":"YkMMTr4W0ibow04I","name":"Put Innocents in Danger","content":"<p>Halcyon City is full of people, and they may be used to the superhuman conflict that riddles the city, but they aren’t immune to it or safe from it. That’s why heroes are needed in the first place—to keep people safe. When Rampage throws a car, it has to go somewhere, and that means people are often put in danger. Putting innocents in danger ups the ante, and gives the heroes a chance to be heroes.</p>","folder":null,"sort":0,"permission":{"default":0,"RZXbWcV7kggw6gJH":3},"flags":{"cf":{"id":"temp_4h5r03e5nxs","color":"#000000"}}}
{"_id":"gQE0SHsotSj5vU3z","name":"Tell them the Possible Consequences and Ask","content":"<p>Sometimes, the path to victory is clear—but it won’t come without taking a few hits along the way. You can always tell a PC exactly what will happen if they follow a particular course of action, giving them a difficult choice to make or a messy option they hadn’t considered. It raises the tension around their choice and decisions, while still keeping things moving forward.</p>","folder":null,"sort":0,"permission":{"default":0,"RZXbWcV7kggw6gJH":3},"flags":{"cf":{"id":"temp_4h5r03e5nxs","color":"#000000"}}}
{"_id":"kOaL7qLh8vjBfOLX","name":"Activate the Downsides of their Abilities and Relationships","content":"<p>Every ability has a downside; every relationship comes with responsibility. Bring those into play to increase the pressure on the PCs. Make the problems and difficulties of each PC’s abilities and relationships come up to counterbalance the benefits.</p>","folder":null,"sort":0,"permission":{"default":0,"RZXbWcV7kggw6gJH":3},"flags":{"cf":{"id":"temp_4h5r03e5nxs","color":"#000000"}}}
{"_id":"nR1zEyKYqWuzf64r","name":"Bring Them Together","content":"<p>The young heroes will do a bang-up job of separating themselves. They’ve all got their own stuff to worry about, their own interests and ideas to pursue. It’s your job to bring ’em back together and connect the disparate elements of their lives so they wind up encountering each other again in surprising places and ways. You don’t have to make them love each other—but you do need to point them at each other.</p>","folder":null,"sort":0,"permission":{"default":0,"RZXbWcV7kggw6gJH":3},"flags":{"cf":{"id":"temp_4h5r03e5nxs","color":"#000000"}}}
{"_id":"o7t08ghJ0DlhpXq1","name":"Make Them Pay a Price for Victory","content":"<p>You can open paths for the heroes to come through victoriously, having another hero or even a villain arrive with a way to succeed—but always at a price. The villain will only help if you give them something you shouldn’t; the hero offers help, but only in exchange for your team agreeing to follow her lead in the future.</p>\n<p> </p>","folder":null,"sort":0,"permission":{"default":0,"RZXbWcV7kggw6gJH":3},"flags":{"cf":{"id":"temp_4h5r03e5nxs","color":"#000000"}}}
{"_id":"pmqVxC2g3qJqRB6i","name":"Turn Their Move Back on Them","content":"<p>Sometimes, all you have to do to make a move is flip around the move a PC just made. They tried to pierce someone’s mask? Great! Pierce theirs, and ask them some questions. They tried to provoke someone? Great! Provoke them, telling them to do something nasty. When you turn their move back on them, always do it as if it was a 10+ result.</p>","folder":null,"sort":0,"permission":{"default":0,"RZXbWcV7kggw6gJH":3},"flags":{"cf":{"id":"temp_4h5r03e5nxs","color":"#000000"}}}
{"_id":"sWhQALFCBAtsAmvH","name":"GM Playbook Moves","content":"<h2>BEACON</h2>\n<p> • Draw attention to their inadequacies </p>\n<p> • Praise their best traits</p>\n<p> • Make them pay for their audacity</p>\n<p> • Compare them to the others</p>\n<p> • Play to their drives</p>\n<h2>BULL</h2>\n<p>• Endanger their love</p>\n<p> • Bolster their rival</p>\n<p> • Reveal dark secrets of their past</p>\n<p> • Attack with someone just like them</p>\n<p> • Swarm with mundane forces</p>\n<h2> DELINQUENT</h2>\n<p> • Put them in chains</p>\n<p> • Give or take an audience</p>\n<p> • Give them conditional love</p>\n<p> • Show them the line</p>\n<p> • Offer a helping hand</p>\n<h2> DOOMED</h2>\n<p> • Mark their doom track</p>\n<p> • Offer a chance to further their cause</p>\n<p> • Remind them of what they could lose</p>\n<p> • Push them to the brink</p>\n<p> • Offer temporary relief with a cost</p>\n<h2> JANUS</h2>\n<p> • Bring their obligations to bear</p>\n<p> • Endanger someone from either life</p>\n<p> • Make their lives cross over</p>\n<p> • Put more obligations on them</p>\n<p> • Take away their mask</p>\n<h2> LEGACY</h2>\n<p> • Remind them of their traditions</p>\n<p> • Compare them to the past</p>\n<p> • Make them answer their family’s concerns</p>\n<p> • Raise expectations on them</p>\n<p> • Honor them</p>\n<h2> NOVA</h2>\n<p> • Remind them of past collateral damage</p>\n<p> • Reveal a terrible truth of their powers</p>\n<p> • Make their powers flare out of control</p>\n<p> • Stoke their conditions</p>\n<p> • Introduce threats only they can tackle</p>\n<h2>OUTSIDER</h2>\n<p>• Draw attention to their differences</p>\n<p> • Make a request from home</p>\n<p> • Introduce a monitor from home</p>\n<p> • Accept and support them in their moments of weakness</p>\n<p> • Provoke their beliefs and practices in tense situations</p>\n<h2> PROTEGE</h2>\n<p>• Convey their mistakes</p>\n<p>• Bestow wisdom, wanted or unwanted</p>\n<p>• Hold up a mirror to them</p>\n<p>• Give them exactly what they need at a cost</p>\n<p>• Endanger their mentor</p>\n<h2>TRANSFORMED</h2>\n<p>• Reject them</p>\n<p>• Show how they are feared or hated</p>\n<p>• Attack them with unthinking hordes</p>\n<p>• Remind them of what they’ve lost</p>\n<p>• See their true self</p>\n<p> </p>","folder":null,"sort":0,"permission":{"default":0,"RZXbWcV7kggw6gJH":3},"flags":{}}
{"_id":"uacO1mEypo2ZJG1j","name":"Make a Playbook Move","content":"<p>Every playbook has its own unique issues and themes to deal with. In BEHIND THE MASKS on page 193, you’ll find individual moves you can make for each playbook, to really push on and bring attention to that playbook’s issues. You can make these moves any time you could make any other GM move.</p>\n<p>Example: Nova—Introduce threats only they can take on</p>","folder":null,"sort":0,"permission":{"default":0,"RZXbWcV7kggw6gJH":3},"flags":{"cf":{"id":"temp_4h5r03e5nxs","color":"#000000"}}}
